August 29 at 11:10 AM ·

Great night at Lancers stadium..
We are so proud of our seniors and all student athletes.

post_text:
The Lakewood Local Administrative Team has been working hard this summer to put together various back-to-school scenarios that maximize learning opportunities for all students and emphasize protocols to protect the safety of staff and students. We have examined best practices for learning in blended and remote models and provided professional development to groups of teachers. We have used guidance from the Governor, the Licking County Health Department and other professional associations to develop safety protocols.

In order to continue to plan for the start of the school year, we ask that you take this brief survey. Your input is critical as we finalize our plans. Please complete by Friday, July 24.

Survey link: https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSc4_uOcyEjKCivjaquAtiVlMGP3sQmuixODzuBZ26RZvblf_Q/viewform

Lakewood Local School District

post_text:
Congratulations to William Kohut for earning a superior rating in the District Science Fair, which allows him to participate in Science Fair at the state level!

William chose to compete in Science Fair on his own. He had to do the research on his own time and even take the day off school (and keep up with his work) to participate. His experiment was called, "Measuring Enzyme Activity In Yeast Catalase" and the question he was trying to answer was how does hydrochloric acid affect the decomposition rate of hydrogen peroxide. William had to design the procedures and carry out the experiment.

William participated in a regional Science Fair at Liberty Union Middle School where he received a superior rating, which allowed him to participate in the District Science Fair. The District Fair was cancelled in person due to Covid-19 and was changed to a virtual science fair. William had to film his experiment and complete his presentation by video. He submitted his video presentation and answered judge's questions digitally.

post_text:
Dear Lakewood Community,
Thank you for your continued support of our district! From those who volunteered their time to call parents, shared information with others, proudly displayed yard sings, and voted, we are grateful to you. The Lakewood Pride Levy Committee, led by Cassie Kane was a pivotal part in educating our voters and we couldn’t have done without their support.

This election has been like no other. From the back and forth of whether or not in person voting would take place until hours before the scheduled election to a possible postponement until June, we have faced a lot of uncertainty. There is one thing that has remained certain though and that is our need for a new elementary building. Although the bond did not pass, that need has not gone away. The Board of Education will meet at a later date to review and discuss how to proceed with the bond.

Once again, thank you for supporting our district.

There is one thing that has remained certain though and that is our need for a new elementary building. Although the bond did not pass, that need has not gone away. The Board of Education will meet at a later date to review and discuss how to proceed with the bond.

Once again, thank you for supporting our district.

Licking County Health Department
April 24 at 2:40 PM ·

The Licking County Health Department (LCHD) continues to partner with Licking County schools during the ongoing COVID-19 pandemic to best protect their students, staff members, and community members.

This includes providing support to school leaders regarding their upcoming graduation ceremonies. Based on guidance issued by the Ohio Department of Education, and in the interest of protecting public health, LCHD recommends that all 2020 graduation ceremonies be conducted virtually.

LCHD does not advise schools to hold in-person graduation ceremonies, virtual events will reduce the spread of the COVID-19 virus among students and attendees. In addition, an in-person ceremony would violate the…

Ohio Governor Mike DeWine recently signed Amended Substitute House Bill 197 into law. This new law is a response to the health risks associated with the Coronavirus outbreak. Among other things, this new law allows public bodies such as boards of education to conduct their meetings using telephone conference, video conference, or other similar technologies.

This law became into effect on March 27, 2020. The Lakewood Local Board of Education is committed to the health, safety, and welfare of our students and their parents, our staff, and our community in general. But even in these times, the Board needs to take certain actions to keep the District operational now and fully functional in the…

Verizon Wireless and AT&T say they're both waiving mobile-data overage fees to help customers deal with the coronavirus pandemic, but the fees will not be waived automatically. Instead, Verizon and AT&T users have to contact the carriers' customer service and say they're experiencing pandemic-related financial hardship to get the fees dropped.

Unlike Verizon and AT&T, T-Mobile and Sprint are providing customers unlimited data during the pandemic without requiring them to contact customer service. T-Mobile announced on March 13 that it is upgrading all customers on limited plans to unlimited smartphone data (excluding roaming) for 60 days. Sprint, which is being acquired by T-Mobile, announced the same day that it is doing the same.

As reported on: https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2020/03/how-to-get-verizon-and-att-data-cap-fees-waived-during-pandemic/

post_text:
There have been questions about the ballot language as it relates the cost of the bond issue. To clarify, the first thing to remember is the millage on the ballot is provided as an estimated average, “…estimated by the County Auditor to average over the repayment period of the bond issue”. With that said, the estimated average millage is 3.8 mills.

Based on the ballot language, 3.80 mills equals $0.38 for each hundred dollars of valuation. Valuation is defined as the “assessed valuation” of property. For a home, the assessed valuation equals 35% of the market value recorded by the County Auditor’s office.

For a home with a market value of $100,000, the assessed value is $35,000. ($100,000 x 35% = $35,000).

To calculate the cost of 3.80 mills, divide $35,000 by $100. So, $35,000/$100 = $350.00.

Then take $350.00 times the $0.38 or $350.00 x .38 = $133/year or $11.08/month.

You can check the value of your home on the Licking County Auditor’s website at: https://lickingcounty.gov/depts/auditor/

post_text:
We had several LMS and LHS students compete in StemFest at The Works this past Saturday.

LMS team members included: Lily Parsons, Josh Holbrook, Emily McDonald, Audrey Harris, Kennedy Helser, Amy Smith, Verena Caudell, Zander Richardson, CJ Reynard, Taysha Pike, Cora Redman, Joel Ellinger, Jayden McNichols, Jathan Holman, Alyce Dunn, Addison Wise, Aiden Maynard, Alexis Vereen, and Lily Eden. Special congratulations to the Bridge Architecture team of Alyce Dunn, Aiden Maynard, Verena Caudell, and Jayden McNichols who won their challenge.

The LHS Science Club participated in the Concrete Challenge. The goal was to engineer the strongest concrete puck possible out of a given amount of Portland cement using a calculated water to concrete ratio and a chosen method of reinforcement.

Lakewood High School’s team consisted of seniors Olivia Ogg and Katie Chittum. When tested, their design was the only one to not crack, chip or break. Ogg and Chittum were awarded first place for this STEMfest challenge. Both received a $1000 scholarship from the Licking County Foundation for their efforts.

We received some great news about our bond levy today from David Conley, an independent financial advisor.

Lakewood bonds might only require 3.30 mills, not the 3.80 mills shown on the ballot. Interest rates have fallen to historical lows meaning the Lakewood bonds could be done at 2.50%, not the 4.00% used to calculate the ballot millage. Approval of the bonds in March would allow the district to lock in these unusually low rates, which would lower the taxes below the stated ballot millage.

Absentee ballot applications are currently being accepted by the Board of Elections. The deadline to request an absentee ballot is three days before the election. If mailed, absentee ballots must be postmarked by the day before the election in order to be counted. You can also return your absentee ballot in-person to your county board of elections before the close of the polls at 7:30 PM on Election Day.

Visit https://www.boe.ohio.gov/licking/absentee-information/absentee-voting/ for more information.

Lakewood Local Schools Seeking Parent and Community Feedback on Next Superintendent

The Lakewood Local Schools Board of Education has hired the search firm Finding Leaders to assist in identifying the district’s next superintendent. Representatives from Finding Leaders will be meeting with various stakeholder groups over the next two weeks. Parents and community members who wish to have a voice in building the profile for the next superintendent are invited to attend a meeting on Wednesday, January 15, at 6:00 PM in the high school auditorium.

We are pleased to share that the Board continues to back our need for a new elementary school. At last night's meeting, the Board voted to approve a resolution that will place a bond issue on the March 2020 ballot. The bond will be for $31,300,000, for 28-years at an estimated 4% interest rate.

We look forward to moving forward with this important issue.

We are pleased to share that the Board continues to back our need for a new elementary school. At last night's meeting, the Board voted to approve a resolution that will place a bond issue on the March 2020 ballot. The bond will be for $31,300,000, for 28-years at an estimated 4% interest rate.

We look forward to moving forward with this important issue.

post_text: The district has said thank you, but those most impacted by last night's vote have not - our students. They would like to say thank you to our voters for passing the operating levy renewal, which allows us to continue to educate them in a way that is consistent with our mission statement: We are a community of learners inspiring each student to explore, grow, and achieve.
text: The district has said thank you, but those most impacted by last night's vote have not - our students. They would like to say thank you to our voters for passing the operating levy renewal, which allows us to continue to educate them in a way that is consistent with our mission statement: We are a community of learners inspiring each student to explore, grow, and achieve.

post_text:
Thank you! First of all, thank you to the community members who came out and voted. Thank you to the Lancer Pride Levy Committee, led by Jessica Corum, for doing a wonderful job educating the members of our community. Let’s not forget our staff, parents, and area supporters who took time to complete a survey, seek out answers to questions, and attend the community forum.

Thank you for passing the operating levy renewal. The monies provided will allow us to continue providing diverse opportunities for our students while maintaining our daily operations. Community support is a vital part of the success of our district.

Although the bond vote did not go the way we had hoped, we are still optimistic for the future of our district. The Board of Education will meet and review how to proceed with the bond levy as a new elementary school is still an important issue that needs attention.

Let’s not forget our staff, parents, and area supporters who took time to complete a survey, seek out answers to questions, and attend the community forum.

Thank you for passing the operating levy renewal. The monies provided will allow us to continue providing diverse opportunities for our students while maintaining our daily operations. Community support is a vital part of the success of our district.

Although the bond vote did not go the way we had hoped, we are still optimistic for the future of our district. The Board of Education will meet and review how to proceed with the bond levy as a new elementary school is still an important issue that needs attention.

Lakewood's mission statement is, "We are a community of learners inspiring each student to explore, grow, and achieve." We achieve that mission by providing the best possible opportunities for our students, and we depend on our operating funds in order to do so. In our final video before election day, Mrs. Dee Martindale, STEM Coordinator, is going to describe some of the opportunities possible due to these funds.

Thank you for allowing us to share our videos with you the past several months. Please remember to vote tomorrow.
